The existence of the OR-CQDs as a shell and SLFCO HF as a core was confirmed by FT-IR investigation. The FT-IR spectra of the specimens inthe wave number range of 200–4000 cm−1 are displayed in Fig. 3 (a). The distinctive bands are mostly seen between 400 (
ν 2
) and 600 (
ν 1
) cm−1 on each spectrum. Mainly at 447 cm−1 and 440 cm−1 (intrinsic stretching vibrations of M−O in octahedral coordination) and at 610 cm−1 and 600 cm−1 (intrinsic stretching vibrations of M−O in tetrahedral coordination) for SLFCO and SLFCO/CQDs, respectively [40]. These prominent peaks indicate the creation of a HF structure [41]. Relative to the spectrum of SLFCO, new bands appeared at higher frequencies for SLFCO/CQDs. The observed bands at ≈1520 cm−1 and a potent broadband over 3400 – 3500 cm−1 are attributed to metal-O-metal and O–H stretching vibration modes [42,43]. The extra peaks observed at 1633 and 1070 cm−1 are assigned to C=O and/or C=C and C-O groups of the OR-CQDs [44,45] which further validates the existence of CQDs in the core–shell sample.
